The Ukrainian parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal a paragraph under the amendment to the Criminal Code, on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted.
The amendment, which would open the way for the release of the imprisoned ex-premier, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of the motion to commute the sentences for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding a allegedly unfavorable treaty with Russia to buy natural gas.
The verdict is not final, the court is to hear the court in December.
Tymoshenko calls the verdict a political revenge on the regime, and the trial has also provoked suspicions of biased in the West.
The proposal to drop out of the Criminal Code, Section 365 on the basis of which the ex-premier was convicted, was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
It needed 226 votes to be approved.
