Iranian students are ready to die for their country's nuclear program.
They created a living shield
Several hundred college students have created a living shield around a nuclear facility in Iran.
With their gesture, they want to express their country's support for their country's nuclear program before a possible Israeli attack.
Students prayed in front of the building on Tuesday at noon and then shouted the deaths of the US and Israel.
Several hundred university students in Iran's Isfahan formed a vibrant shield on Tuesday around the Issahan nuclear technology center, where uranium is being processed.
They are thus clear that they are ready to defend their country’s nuclear program with their own lives.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) said in a recent report that Iran does not appear to have stopped seeking a nuclear weapon.
A possible attack on Iran's nuclear facilities are being talked about in Israel.
At noon, before entering the Isfahan nuclear facility, the students prayed and then shouted deaths to America and Israel.
In the event of an attack that would be to cripple Iran’s nuclear program as much as possible, according to the Israeli press, in addition to the Isfahan center, the target would also be a facility in Natanz, where the uranium is enriched.
Diet of an obese child: does not eat and dinner sausages
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, with an excess weight of 9 percent of schoolchildren, and 5 percent of children are obese.
Obese children usually come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, as the current survey showed.
It is again shown how important it is for the healthy development of a person to the environment in which he grows, and the patterns with which he is surrounded.
On the tables in obese children, for example, sausages appear up to half as often as in the families of children with normal weight.
Fried fries had for dinner the day before the research associated with an awareness-raising event called Obesity is not a coincidence of more than 19 percent of obese.
In families of fat people, it is also not a habit to play sports, which applies to most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children responded that their parents find time for active movement at least once a week.
Survey among 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of the Obesity event is no accident, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand schoolchildren from 4 to 8 classes have participated in the project.
Proper eating and getting enough exercise in the family is one of the defining factors that causes a dramatically rising number of overweight or even obese children.
"Only half of respondents said, for example, that they eat five times a day in breakfast-snack-lude-snake mode, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition," reads one of the survey results.
No breakfast and evening sausage
Experts point out that relative details are also essential for healthy development, such as regular time for family breakfasts.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of families of schoolchildren eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats alone.
And the worst part was the discovery that a tenth of households don't eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in the families of obese children, unhealthy fries are much more often consumed.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of children surveyed regularly do sports, their parents’ result was less than half that was 15 percent.
Build your diet
The next part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls out of 13 schools) to build their own diet according to their own taste and their own opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from the point of view of healthy nutrition to the ideal."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes.
"The great popularity of sweet sodas is particularly alarming," the final report said.
For lunch as the main dish, pasta won just above the poultry.
However, children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetable dishes is also low.
Inclination to health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the end of the awareness-raising lecture Obesity, there was a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition in many cases," the results of the project said.
This was striking, for example, in sweet lemonades, where more children would start to prefer ordinary water.
Children also ticked poultry and fish as the main meal of the day in the questionnaire and would limit sweet foods and dumplings.
