In Need for Speed: The Run races across America.
Reviews
Originally a carefree ride turns into a routine morning journey on a shift due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
The ambition was largely fulfilled, but it is no use when no one clearly wanted to do anything extra.
The new episode, subtitled The Run, aroused high expectations before it was released.
He promised that the long-standing racing series Need for Speed would once again move a bit in a new direction, and from the playable demos it appeared to be a game that would not have to be just in the genre of action racing.
We were also curious to see how the inserted passages would turn out of the car and take place on foot.
As usual with the NFS series, however, many are a little different in the result than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole drags down a few unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more or less for several years.
So it's not actually mistakes, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced into a story whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal character and as a solution is offered participation in an illegal race across America.
Behind the wheel you get behind the wheel on the west coast in San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea brings with it some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then to more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is on a different track and the given stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t feel like the game is always the same thing.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, even though the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-renowned.
But driving across the desert, autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains seem visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are diversched from time to time with some atypical element.
In the desert, for example, you can get in a sandy storm, which greatly reduces visibility.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be careful not to be covered by an avalanche.
In addition, individual races are put quite well behind each other.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of opponents (esseually a classic race), then you catch up again (classic duel with stopwatches) and then there is a duel with a single opponent.
From time to time, the police get involved in this, which makes your entire efforts even more difficult.
New is the passages outside the car.
Rather, it is just such interactive animations, where Jack usually flees in front of someone and you have to help him in this by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
However, he will be surprised that there are much fewer of these passages in the game than you would expect (specifically, perhaps only three).
As a result, however, it is to the benefit of the cause, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and in the context of the above ranks is one of the elements that diversify the game.
The driving model goes in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that it is definitely not anything nowadays, but it cannot be said that it is a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will need to look elsewhere.
But the more active racing local riding model still suits quite well, even though we would be able to find better in the competition.
So much so everything in perfect order.
But problems are starting to occur after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collisible model is no longer very well.
We do not expect a game of this type to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if practically before no impact on any object has the slightest idea how your car will behave, then probably not everything is in order.
Typically, when overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, sometimes you only slightly lick each other, but at other times in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even a superbath.
Thanks to the restart system, it does not particularly matter, but it will upset you reliably.
Restarts are designed so that if you smashed or go far off the track, the game will throw you back on the last clue on the track.
But only five restarts are available in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race again from scratch.
It is more of an aid in case something goes wrong rather than relying on them.
But sometimes even restarts do not help, they will be solved by the need to learn the given section of the race by heart.
The big malaise of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some bends need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply can’t fit into them.
At other times, you will meet "civil" cars at a given place always in the same configuration, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It upsets especially in situations where you can see how between two oncoming cars the opponent passes in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to go around or brake them.
It does not matter when you reach them, because it is "calculted" so that the situation always occurs just before your nose.
Opponents also have another advantage.
During the whole time of playing, you will come across several places where, again no matter what time, the same opponent will always overtake you in the same place.
It hits the most at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
An opponent must get there in front of you, perhaps at any cost.
When he rides in front of you, he makes it worse for you to see on-the-going cars, so you're probably going to smash you there a few times.
It is possible to understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-fuelled, but the execution is so obvious that it will reliably quickly disgust you.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes so action-packed that sometimes you literally don't manage to watch where what's flying.
And it basically does not matter whether the concept with fifty unique tracks, the sorting of races so that boredom has no chance, or anything else.
An unconventional idea is to change cars during races.
You have to pay attention to gas stations at the roads, because that is where you can change the car, even though in the vast majority of cases you can do with what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American breakers on straight highways and exotic supercars for technical driving, for example, on winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with the mode of challenges, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common to challenges and story.
Various items are unlocked for a higher level of driver: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for the profile.
At the same time, it is again connected to the online Autologist feature, which compares your achieved results with other players and provides other community features.
One of the other difficult-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you get to the metro tunnel (so be it), where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (so be it).
On the speedometer, the numbers flash between 150 and 200 km/h (so be it) and a subway train comes in from the back and uncompromisingly scraps you.
In the newsroom, we probably have a discussion about whether no one really thought a little bit about the creation of the game, or whether the authors think of us as really such a big idiot.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
It is so frustrating that in some more tense moments the voting decreases, and in some cases quite tragically.
However, this applies especially to crashes with a larger number of participants, when smooth imaging would no longer be of any use to you anyway.
The sound side is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible scale of a rather younger audience, the soundtrack was created from the category "each dog of another village", but it can be assumed that in order to listen to music, the game will probably not be bought.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so embarrassing.
If the game avoids completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
This is how the game works unfinished.
Fun is definitely good, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will slap you in the eye by the power of the airport spotlight.
Choirs of Charles University will be performed at the concert Students of Velvet
The combination of the celebrations of International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with the musical experience is offered for the third time by the Festa Academica festival.
During this time, he will present himself in twenty high school and university choirs.
The main focus of the festival is two concerts held on November 17.
"Charles University has a big part in the festival."
"Among the participating choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities, the Rector Václav Hampl will sit in the festival committee," said Jakub Čaloun, the head of the organizing team.
The highlight of the whole festival is a free concert of secondary school choirs, which will take place on 17 November from 14 o'clock in the area in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes the composition of the important Czech jazzman Karel Růžička Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, a concert "Students of Velvet" will take place in the ceremonial premises of the National House in Vinohrady, where university choirs, including choirs of Charles University, will perform.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate International Student Day with dignity and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and develop the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organizer is the Union of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Jan Kepler Grammar School.
Bohuslav Svoboda, the Mayor of the Capital City of Prague and the Rector of Charles University, Václav Hampl, took over the auspices of the whole event.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to the ceremonial concerts, the schedule also offers a number of musical meetings, student happenings, matina and other shows.
Detailed information can be found on the festival website www.festaacademic.cz
