How the prices of tours have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in what was then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
At that time, travel agencies overwhelmingly only sold tours to the countries of the Socialist Bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea by the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime sided with the West and the journey of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia was subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely even within the socialist countries.
In the event that a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand a queue overnight with a sleeping bag or have a "good aquaintances" in the travel agency.
But even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for trips to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so it was not possible to raise funds (the Western currency) for the trip to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
However, by far the most often Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that Czechs bought and this custom survives to this day.
The travel of Czechs has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible to travel freely to us for the most popular Croatia until 1989, as it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
In the early 90’s, the visa requirement was lifted to neighbouring Western European countries, which started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria’s Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to see it at least for a while.
In Paris, for example, Czechs slept in parks in tents, because our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of the travel of Czechs at this time was to carry their own food, canned food, sausages, etc. in order to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which was finally able to freely buy the western currency after many dans for years.
However, our standard of living and with that average salaries increased, resulting around 1997 at another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have regularly started preparing tours with charter flights since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper thanks to the possibility of arranging quantity discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 90's of the last century, Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first ever direct charter flight to exoticism was dispatched from the Czech Republic, it was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm far-flung countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100 thousand Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and thus our country has definitely ranked among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time in history and spent more than 15 thousand on the first time in history, including the cost of the stay. CZK per person.
