The adversity of climate has slowed the economy
During the first year of the reign of Mario López Valdez, unemployment and unreliability rose in Sinaloa, foreign investment and the economy with them decreased
2011 will be in the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of Mario López Valdez's reign, which is called the government of change. This government has brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, but due to the unfavorable climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, there was no growth and even the main indicators of economic development declined.
Low February temperatures caused millions in losses in agriculture, limiting the growth opportunities of the state economy, responsible for reducing economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year. In the area of agriculture, there was a historic decline of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the report on the damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded on 582 835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 780.0% were completely destroyed and partial damage was found to be 21.07%. The main destroyed crops include vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant rise in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state recorded an increase in the first three quarters. From January to March, 55 053 of the population of the state of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August, rising further, reaching 6.19%, representing around 74,000 unemployed. Compared to the first quarter, the number of unemployed increased by 18 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa is due to several factors. According to Gerard López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps taken at the level of public policy.
“We are witnessing an increasing unemployment that is related to various factors. These include, among other things, the loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints as a result of legislation approved by the Congress in connection with the fight against money laundering. It’s not easy for people who illegally seize dollars, it’s not easy for them to make money, invest them, or use them for something.”
Stopping migration
López Cervantes said the demographic factor is also contributing to the increase in unemployment.
“The number of people going abroad to work in the United States has decreased, both for reasons of difficult entry and also because even if these people get abroad, it’s hard for them to get a job. So people stay and demand work from our state, so unemployment is rising,” he said.
Unreliable
Analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the increasing unreliability that prevails in terms of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of employed residents in the state work without paying benefits to social security administration.
Unemployment and unreliability are added to other features of the labour market, such as low salaries. In this administrative territory, the lowest salaries from all over the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Labour and Social Planning Department.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa until September was 5 352 peseta, well below the national average, which is at 7 375 pesset.
Shortening of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, the most significant drop in foreign direct investment in 10 years was also recorded in 2011. According to the Treasury Department, between January and June, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,697, representing a decrease of 87.74% from $5,143,33 $317 per year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government lists investments of 17 280 million pesetas per year. These investments were mainly directed to services businesses.
Debt
In the context of the scenario of a downturn in the economy, the government of this state asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso. This would be earmarked for investment in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2 600 million peso. By November, no debt gains had been recorded, in any sector of the state economy.
Reaction
According to the representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés pointed to the lack of government management capabilities.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the government of the state itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really tiny this year. We need to work hard to get back the land we've lost this year. In 2012, we must redouble our efforts, lacking the harmonisation of the efforts of all of us and, in particular, the proper and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better,” he said.
The Slowness of the Economy
Loredo López said events like frosts at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and curtailed its development and growth.
"Weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown in the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore dynamism, which would allow for an acceptable level of movement for processes, products and services. That is why at the end of the year we found ourselves well below the expected forecasts," he said.
Redefinition of mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriart, president of the People's Republic of Mexico's Employer Confederation in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed towards more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we're observing that we're working. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be prepared in which the objectives and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resources that Sinaloa has is mobilized," he said.
The work that is ahead of us
President Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of a future that would better guide the government's efforts.
"Generally, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, some progress has been made in economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan," he said.
He said the current administration has shown progress in terms of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that make it possible to claim that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that the work done here is visible and I believe that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us," he said.
