New Italian government to be appointed on Wednesday
Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that holds the country over the abyss of economic catastrophe.
Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that holds the country over the abyss of the economic catastrophe and which has put the eurozone into danger.
The presidential palace issued a report in which it announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he could form a government.
It is expected to introduce a government mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks he had with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
"The framework is now well marked," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, i.e. in much shorter periods than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to fight the political and financial crisis, due to which the amount of debt has climbed to an unsustainable level.
The new administration, led by the former European Commissioner, Monti, must approve the tough austerity package required by European leaders. This is the only way to restore the deremilined credibility of Italy.
There's a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry. Due to market instability, interest on Italian BTP bonds exceeded a 10-year maturity of a 7 percent threshold, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to apply for bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, chairwoman of the Italian employer's Confindustrio organization, told reporters after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this government is the last resort for Italy to get out of this burning situation.
Monti's hopes of success were significantly multiplied by Silvio Berlusconi's PDL support, which the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts are destined for good results,” Angelina Alfano, the secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because up to this moment a number of its members have opposed a government with a technocratic majority, assembled by Monti.
Support for the Parliament
Monti's new government must have strong support for parliament in order to push for unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Foreign Banks Association has added to the pressure, warning that Monti's failure could be a disaster.
Monti opened on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women's organizations.
The round of negotiations will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed President Napolitan on Sunday, allowing very rapid progress in response to the crisis.
After a brief decline from the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian bond interest rates have returned to the critical threshold, responding to the uncertainty of whether the new prime minister would be successful.
Saving Italy, whose public debt is €1.8 trillion, would be beyond the possibilities of the eurozone’s current financial reserves.
Monti said his government should stay in power until the next election, which is scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that say politicians will only give him time to carry out reforms and then declare early elections.
Monti said he would like to integrate politicians into his cabinet, but the big parties insist that this government must be composed only of experts to take Italy out of the difficulties the country has gone into because of financial pressure.
Political sources have said that mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicate the attempt to integrate political figures into the government.
