Quintet has included the country in its tour on the occasion of the celebration of twenty years of existence
"A journey to Costa Rica is a dream that comes true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the group is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true for them.
This is what the bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The band is located on the South American continent as part of a tour on the occasion of celebrating the 20th anniversary of its existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20.
On the day, he will perform at the National Stadium from 19:30 along with the angel group The X and national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from an interview whose entire transcript can be found on the website La Nación on the Internet.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The road to Costa Rica is also our dream that becomes reality.
We are hardly the second time in South and Central America, and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It's a beautiful country and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we're very happy to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally adore the group here, fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensively.
What do you think of your most rocky supporters?
Thank you for standing with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and sorry that it took us so long.
Some people talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it cause more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we've put in the last 21 years have emerged in a matter of weeks.
We have put in some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that we got in shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you know Costa Rica and her waves that are suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfers friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. And so we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no restrictions on what we can't do.
We will try to perform the best possible show with various songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and introduce a good and diverse repertoire to our fans.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why?
I think that partly it is because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose what songs we play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven’t played for a long time, we focus on them and we’re also surprised, because we’ll think about why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of artistic career.
When you look back, it's hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, I'm sure.
First of all, I don’t think any of us could have imagined that we would be in a big rock band and that we would stay in it for more than 20 years. That sounds like a dream.
We realize how much we have been given and are moved to be able to continue to play together.
We love each other and love to create music.
We are lucky to be able to look at the places we have always wanted.
We couldn't have turned out better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group in which the greats are represented.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn’t happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups come from one city at once.
We are proud of this and we are honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play with some of them.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky to be our friends all and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think first of all we are lucky to be in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are constantly interested in each other play a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open the musical paths that leave everyone sufficient freedom to experiment.
We believe in each other, we appreciate the music of the other and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship with the word glory was not easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew, it was gradually becoming easier to find a balance.
We try not to go too much on tour, because it is very easy to fall into this trap of the crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people have come for the sake of music, you will remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You mustn't get carried away by being famous, rock stars. Neither of us ever really cared about this.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and in the beginning it was something spectacular.
We've been a band for three years and we've never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember Andy how incredible he was, how I laughed at him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, laugh, talk about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person and we miss him very much.
The national band Las Robertas will be tasked with starting a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as their opening act?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several suggestions and we liked this group the most. That's why we're curious to see what Las Robertas will offer live and have to be very fun.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he's adding the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influences you as a bassist?
Lots of people.
I'm the first to think of Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I could talk about bassists I like all night.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge, even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've all always felt slightly apart from the word grunge.
When you say grunge, I imagine the groups I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that were created at the same time. And if even today music is valid, it's something great, because it's music worth listening to, and groups like Mudhoney today play better music than ever before.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly crumpled character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
This is interesting because I feel that there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe, which are considered very bleak, although they can sound positive.
For both of them, when Ed played them, I cried, and they are songs deeply dark.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent just that for me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
