Fujimori was hospitalized again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for the muscle loss he suffers from the lower extremities, his attending physician reported.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who is serving a sentence of 25 years imprisonment for human rights violations committed by his government (1990 - 2000), suffers from several diseases, including language cancer, for which he has been operated four times and is already under control by doctors.
Member of Parliament Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Canal N television station that Fujimori will undergo tests at the National Institute of No Plastic Diseases within three days, where they should find out why it hurts and why it loses strength in the lower extremities.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion, Fujimori could receive clemency for humanitarian reasons, however, the former president himself does not want a pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated four times due to tongue cancer, he dropped 18 kilograms, and these problems were joined by other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst on the pancreas, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor enumerated.
Fujimari has been serving a sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people killed by murder squads of troops operating illegally in his first years of his reign.
Mujica on a visit to Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation, led by Uruguayan President, José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday. Its aim is to achieve the expansion of trade between the two nations and to touch on the political themes of the region.
Mujica will meet with her Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of a large-scale visit to meetings with representatives of politics, commerce and representatives of the Uruguayan community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan Presidential Office.
A meeting between the two presidents in Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political affairs between the two countries," the Uruguayan presidential office posted on its website.
According to local media, Mujico will try to get Calderón to support Uruguay in a dispute with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy placed the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in Cannes, France.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that will continue to remain in the position of tax havens would be excluded from the international community. The statement prompted a rejection of Uruguay and consultation with the ambassador in that European country.
Mexico has been presided over the G20 since November. The G20 is a group made up of the most powerful and developed countries in the world. Since January this year, an agreement has been reached with the Latin American country to exchange information to prevent double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has been seeking to specify fiscal exchange agreements to access the "blacklist" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), to which are countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of tax cooperation.
From a commercial point of view, Mexico and Uruguay have concluded the FTA Agreement since 2004, thanks to which the exchange of goods between the two countries has been strengthened.
