Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome presented details of an air accident in which the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others, were killed.
The Secretariat for Communications and Traffic (SCT) reported that the results of the investigation into the accident, in which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora was killed and seven others showed that the helicopter hit the terrain with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communication and Transport, said the pilot said before taking off the plane, the pilot stated that the climatic conditions allow for the flight.
"The parts that appear suggest that the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, the wings were entangled in the branches of the trees 25 meters from where the unit lost the hull."
He also reported that the unit was intended for 19 people, therefore it met all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, he said that based on an investigation carried out in the area of impact, no parts were found on the ground.
"The search was found that parts of the aircraft were not located in another place, so the plane hit the mainland as whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, met all requirements for the transport of persons.
The terrain shows a slope with an inclination of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get the results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation can take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, CEO of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the moment of the crash, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at a cruise rate and the accident occurred on a soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a common flyby operation," he said.
At the press conference, the representative of the SCT Pérez Jácome listed six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in AICM state adequate conditions at take-off, in line with the aircraft advances towards the border, between DF and the State Mexico there were visible layers of clouds at low heights.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds, the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility up to the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinators of the impact and the last recording of the helicopter from the radar coincide, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the flight trajectory before the impact.
Dispersal of aircraft residues in limited territory:
The information we currently have available allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a flat trajectory and from the side.
A sketch of the scattering of the remnants of the aircraft suggests that at the time of the impact on the mainland, the helicopter was complete.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident that evidenced that there had been an explosion or a fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that several contacts may have occurred with the mainland.
During the field work, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9200 feet above the sea, the terrain is sloping, the height of the inclination goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photos show footage in which there was likely to be a breakdown along the route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search around the accident, in an area that is more extensive than the territory of the demarcation, the remains of a helicopter were not found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state where the helicopter was still complete.
Mexico's Health Insurance Institute launches gene research that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for the obesity of children and adolescents. Research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to uncover a gene causing obesity in children and young people. The research, called "The Genetics of Obesity in Children and Teenagers," will allow you to obtain results regarding overweight.
In a report by the head of the Research Medical Unit in the field of biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and pupils of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestava) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, who has or has no right to participate in the research, can also participate in the research. People can come to participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de Mexico, where each sibor will be carried out from 8 a.m. to the youth tests.
He stressed that the research began at the Sports Centre Cuahutémoc (Mexican state) and from 8. On October, this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualcóolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
Once data is obtained from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people and thus prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are given anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose levels, trigliceride, cholesterol, insulin and genes are examined (trying to identify genes that are involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflects health workers' concerns over an alarming increase in baby weight.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys had a 77% increase in obesity and 47% for girls. There was also a dramatic increase in the case of overweight', an expert from IMSS said.
He stated that one of the reasons for finding indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in genes that are responsible for the emergence of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, which will determine whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of wrinkles of dark color (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-sugar conditions.
The information is still confidential, doctors pass it on to parents in writing and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order for their children to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle meaning a lack of daily physical activity, all-day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Overweight is also caused by a large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in the Asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry, UNAM creates modified asphalt with polymers, creating a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving were properly cared for, it would not have to be repaired almost 200 thousand potholes after each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de Mexico, said Rafael Herrera Nájer, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemical Technology (FQ) from UNAM, who at the same time added that if the design and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even could be removed completely.
In his lecture, the Technological cause of potholes he uttered within the International Year of Chemistry announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalt with polymers, which should create a mixture with similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example, in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with high molecular weight, which are called asphaltene, and others with low molecular weight, which are called mortars. Together, they give the asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees has a high viscosity, and at 50 degrees it is almost in solid state, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in the Ciudad de Mexicoco were covered with flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the uppermost layers there is an asphalt insert, consisting of small stones embedded in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms a liner is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or when creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to spread well.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would have decomposed even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the last layer called a cloak, consisting of fine stones, i.e. sand also embedded in asphalt, is placed on the asphalt liner.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle rims, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the roadway.
Since it will be subjected to a large load as part of the paving, the mantle must have a sufficient thickness and be careful of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. Water, in particular, has a big impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is moist, the water spreads inwards and is hard to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the pavement and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that during the formation of potholes, the film of the cloak is the first to be damaged, and only then the asphalt insert is damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one point, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first signs using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in the formation of potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of paving must correspond to the load of vehicles and it must be guaranteed that this burden will not be exceeded. This is the only way to prevent the frequent formation of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do, and the research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and allow you to easily repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
