As in other cases, the effects of the announcement appear somewhat disproportionate to the truth of incapacity for work.
In fact, these have been the subject of permanent surveillance since 2002 and the political onslaught that bore fruit.
The French are not more sick than elsewhere in Europe.
Let’s stop by a few official numbers.
According to Caisse nationale d'assurance maladie (CNAM - state health insurance company), more than 237 million euros of daily refunds were paid in 2006.
According to the French Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Care, daily refunds with their 11.3 billion euros accounted 5% of health expenditure in health care in 2008.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity allowances and accidents at work and 54% concerned incapacity for work, i.e. 6.2 billion euros.
Only 2.5% of the cost of health care.
According to an Alma Consulting study, the French had an average of 14.5 days of incapacity for work in 2010 compared to 17.8 days in 2009.
The diameter that hides certain deviations: another poll published in r. 2007 on the website dealing with the job opportunities Monster.com showed that 75% of the 40,000 respondents told that they had not chosen any day of incapacity for work.
Another study, this time conducted by sickness insurance institutions, clarifies that in r. 2010 37.8% of incapacity for work was less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to 1 month, 15% from 1 to three months and 11% lasted longer.
When compared to their European neighbours, French employees are no more susceptible to incapacity for work than elsewhere.
One long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS (National Research Centre) researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001 the total absence (from health reasons or not) oscillated between 10% and 11,8% in France versus 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the UK and 18% in the Netherlands.
Cheating on incapacity for work is only a very small part compared to black work.
When it comes to fraud, these are only small scales.
Strengthening legislation from r. 2002 has caused systematic controls aimed at incapacity for work for more than 45 days.
In 2008, CNAM noted that at 1.5 million inspections, 13.8% of the 285,000 were carried out due to short-term incapacity for "unjustified or too long," i.e. 37 050 cases.
In the case of systematically controlled incapacity for more than 45 days, 11% of cases of "unadapted or unauthorised" were counted per 1.2 million checks, i.e. 132 000.
Thus, a total of 169 000 "unjustified" cases for several million employees who had incapacity for work.
A number that represents much less than a number expressing black work.
According to UMP MP Dominique Tiano, author of the June report on this issue, this figure would represent 9 to 15 billion euros missing in the collection of taxes per year, i.e. more than the total amount of daily refunds and thus infinitely more than the fraud associated with the latter.
