Recently, this was an administrative harassment, the object of which was foreign students, which became topical when the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of May 23) declared that France "does not need foreign talents, bricklayers and waitresses".
But so far, it has rarely been discussed at the point of the economy.
It must be said that in this area there is a rather broad consensus between the left and the right.
On the right, Jacques Chirac reported to the tone in 1976 with his statement that "900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country where 2 million immigrants are" and on the left Michel Rocard, when in 1990 he said that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world."
The only difference is the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of hordes of Polish plumbers on French territory was shared both on the right and to the left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that we are tolerating to provide immigrants.
In its program, François Hollande confines itself to banalities, indicating that joint developments will make it possible to solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may apply in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in their recently published work synthesizing the latest knowledge of immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.): there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages, and employment in the countries that accept immigrants.
Restrictions on immigration are crippling growth and harming employment.
Concerns about the effects caused by migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially those less qualified, and create pressure to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants are much more complemented than substitutes for French employees by doing work in sectors with staff shortages.
Fewer qualified immigrants in sectors that do not attract French employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors in which education is not enough to offer jobs.
Positive impact on wages
Like the surgeon, he will have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, these additions between the French and migrants cause the arrivals of immigrants to have a positive effect on the wages and employment of French employees.
Giovanni Peri calculated that growth in migration movements by 1% will lead to a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And yet it does not take into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems in European countries on average 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labour Organisation estimates that in Germany, one migrant will bring a net contribution (income minus expenditure) to public budgets in its entire life, 150000 euros.
Nicolas Sarkozy expressed his wish at the beginning of his term to go for the lack of growth with his teeth.
These teeth used to deter immigrants have had the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a rare and very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, even though it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, during the 20th century, the tragedy of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulags, but also Franca in Spain, Salazar, Portugal and colonels in Greece.
