Nord Stream, a new harbor of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to operate.
It must supply gas equal to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, among them 4 heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new gas pipeline that will be directly united by Russia and Germany under the sea.
Symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned together by the control wheel of the valve of the control input of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will start flowing into Western Europe every year with the first 1-224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the federal state of Mecklemburk-Pomerania.
The second pipe, which must be completed at the end of r. 2012, it will allow the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is an amount equal to the entire French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly objected to the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow it to deliver gas directly to Germany without being run by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At once, these two countries are losing their power somewhat: the possibility of pushing Russia with the threats of having access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it the strongest when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", citing the alliance between Hitler and Stalin in the occupation of Poland in r. 1939.
It means saying that this is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained more certainty of its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe energy, because the project created cracks between Europeans from the East and West.
Russia managed barely 5 years ago to assert its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western states with high gas consumption, the deposits of which are coming to an end.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically,” François Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of this pipeline, demonstrating at what point large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply site.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The undersea pipe is made of steel with a concrete cladding to protect against the anchors of seagoing vessels.
It rests at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, minefields dating from World War 2 had to be avoided.
“For the safety of them, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase the measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing like 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted anywhere on its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project manager rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see the Russian state society settle permanently off their coast.
"In the event of a defect, we will stop the passage of gas in less than 1 minute," explains Jens Müller.
In case of leaks, the gas contained in the pipeline leaks into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely to builders, since the welds were designed so that the leakage is created every 100 000 years.
Checking the state of the gas pipeline from the outside is carried out by the underwater robot pulled by the ship, while the inside of the gas pipeline is controlled by the device that circulates inside.
This cougar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the end of the journey for the whole three days of the journey at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of the metal parts.
The remote pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without the need for the slightest repair.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake, remains the lead.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream tasked with the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company for five years with a contract that can be renewed, all its gas transport capacities.
“Gazprom will profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of real gas being transported,” said Jens Müller.
Financing of the pipeline construction was secured from 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs have risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be returned, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline rises from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the outlet gate of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before being transported to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When the full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and in r. 2012 6 million.
